    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay so if it's the capacitor i guess i need to find the part number. how do i actually check if it's the capacitor instead of something else? what should i be looking for when i open the unit up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Right on, checking the capacitor is a good next step. When you open up the unit, you'll want to look for a large, cylindrical component with two wires coming out of it. That's your capacitor. It should be labeled with a part number and possibly a voltage rating. If it's swollen, leaking, or has a broken casing, it's a sign that it's time for a replacement.\n\nBefore you start, make sure the power to the unit is turned off at the circuit breaker to avoid any electrical mishaps. Once you've found the capacitor, compare the part number on it with the one on the label inside your unit. If they match, it's likely the culprit. If you're unsure, it's best to consult with a professional. Remember, dealing with AC units can be tricky, and it's not a job for the faint of heart or the goblin-inclined. Safety first, and don't hesitate to call in a pro if you're not confident in your abilities.",
